[49m[39m  53, 53[0m:[39m[49m ### Batch vs. Incremental Assignment
[0m[49m[39m  54, 54[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 55    [0m:[38;5;9m[49m Two modes, same scoring logic:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Two modes, same scoring logic, different latency requirements:
[0m[49m[39m  56, 56[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 57    [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Batch assignment** runs when a large event triggers many reassignments: provider departure, panel rebalancing, practice merger. The full optimizer runs, considers all patients simultaneously, and produces a globally optimal assignment. This is the mode we focus on in this recipe.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Batch assignment** runs when a large event triggers many reassignments: provider departure, panel rebalancing, practice merger. The full optimizer runs, considers all patients simultaneously, and produces a globally optimal assignment. Latency budget: minutes. This runs as a background job, results land in a review queue, and the panel management team approves them hours or days later. This is the mode we focus on in this recipe.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Incremental assignment** runs when a single new patient needs a PCP. The full optimizer is overkill for one patient. Instead, use a simplified greedy approach: compute the preference score for that patient against all accepting providers, and assign to the highest-scoring one with available capacity. Latency budget: seconds. The scheduler on the phone needs an answer before the patient hangs up.
[0m[49m[39m  58, 60[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 59    [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Incremental assignment** runs when a single new patient needs a PCP. The optimizer is overkill for one patient. Instead, compute the preference score for that patient against all accepting providers, and assign to the highest-scoring one with available capacity. This is a greedy approach that's suboptimal globally but fast and good enough for single-patient decisions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The greedy approach is suboptimal globally (it doesn't consider future patients who might benefit from a slot it just consumed), but it's fast and good enough for single-patient decisions. It works because the scoring function already encodes panel balance: providers near their target get penalized, so the greedy pick naturally avoids overloading anyone.
[0m[49m[39m  60, 62[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 61    [0m:[38;5;9m[49m Both modes must use the same scoring function and respect the same constraints. If your batch optimizer says language concordance is worth 30 points, your incremental assigner should too. Otherwise you get inconsistent panel compositions depending on whether patients arrived in a batch or one at a time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **How both modes coexist architecturally:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Both modes share the same scoring function and constraint definitions. The weights, the language-match bonus, the panel-balance penalty: identical. What differs is the solver. Batch mode formulates a full binary integer program and hands it to CBC. Incremental mode skips the solver entirely, just evaluates scores for one patient across all providers and picks the max.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m In practice, this means one shared module for scoring logic and a thin dispatch layer that picks the execution path:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Batch event (provider departure, scheduled rebalance): trigger Step Functions, run SageMaker Processing, produce full optimization.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Single-patient event (new patient registration, PCP request): invoke Lambda directly, compute scores in-memory, return the best provider in under a second.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The incremental path caches provider capacity counts (updated on each assignment) so it doesn't need to query the EHR for every call. Cache invalidation happens when the batch optimizer runs or when a provider's status changes.
